The Tampita Viharaya at the Gurubebila Purana Viharaya is built on short granite stumps as the center part of a larger building. A narrow circumambulating path with no protective rail surrounds the image house. The roof covers both the Tampita Viharaya and the outer hall.
Wanguthanna Sri Sunandaramaya is a Buddhist temple in Watareka, Mawathagama with an ancient Tampita Viharaya built during the Kandyan Kingdom. The temple lies off Rambkkama – Mawathagama road, 12 km off Rambukkana and 10km off Mawathagama. To reach the temple
Muwandeniya Sri Dammaloka Purana Viharaya consists of a Tampita Viharaya built during the Kandyan era. Unfortunately the Tampita Viharaya at the Muwandeniya temple has been completely rebuilt and has lost its architectural and archaeological value.
Selagama Bulathwatta Purana Viharaya consists of a Tampita Viharaya built during the Kandyan era. Unfortunately the Tampita Viharaya has been completely rebuilt. The image house is no longer on pillars but on a cemented platform built burying the pillars.
The Tampita Viharaya at the Malagamuwa Udugodagama Purana Viharaya is comparatively small. A narrow circumambulating path with no protective rail surrounds the image house.
Yataththawala Bodhiwansaramaya Rajamaha Viharaya is an ancient Buddhist temple belonging to the era of the Dambadeniya kingdom with a Tampita Viharaya belonging to the Kandyan Era.
Yakarawatta Purana Siddha Pattini Tampita Devalaya is one of the oldest and respected Pattini Devalaya in the Sathkoralaya (Kurunegala District). According to legend, Yakarawatta Devalaya is over 500 years old.
Lunukadawella Rajamaha Viharaya is a Buddhist temple with an ancient Tampita Viharaya lying in in Rikillagamuwa. According to legend Prince Gemunu on his march to Vijithapura to attack Elara’s last hold had rested with his army at Lunukadawella and it is said that this temple was built by him for his soldiers to perform Buddhist rituals.
  Badagamuwa Thorayaya Ancient Viharaya is a Buddhist temple with an ancient Tampita Viharaya built during the era of king Kirthi Sri Rajasinghe (1747 – 1781) of Kandyan Kingdom.  The temple lies bordering Badagamuwa Forest on the Kurunegala – Dambulla
Talammehera Sri Sunandarama Purana Viharaya is an Buddhist temple with an ancient Tampita Viharaya on 10 granite pillars built during the Kandyan Era.
Sapugaskanda Sri Vijaya Sunandarama Rajamaha Viharaya is an ancient Buddhist temple lying on a high rock plateau in the Wadakada area. The current temple has been build during the era of king Sri Vijaya Rajasinghe (1739 -1747) of the Kandyan kingdom
According to folklore Wathuwaththa Sri Sunandarama Purana Tampita Rajamaha Viharaya has been built by king Keerthi Sri Rajasinhe (1747 – 1781) as a wish granted to a villager of the Wathuwatta village.
Sri Sudharmarama Purana Viharaya is a Buddhist temple with an ancient Tampita Viharaya belonging to the Kandyan era. The temple lies in the Dandagamuwa village just 3.5 km off Kuliyapitiya, 24 km off Narammala and 25 km from Madampe.
Sri Siddhartharama Rajamaha Viharaya is a Buddhist temple with an ancient Tampita Viharaya belonging to the Kandyan era. The temple lies in Werahera off Yakwila between Pannala and Kuliyapitiya. It lies about 6 km from Pannala and 15 km from Kuliyapitiya.
Madahapola Sri Rathanapalaramaya Purana Tampita Viharaya is a Buddhist temple with an ancient Tampita Viharaya belonging to the Kandyan era. The temple is modernized with no artifacts of ancient times other than the Tampita Viharaya which too is now covered with a new structure.
Palugamuwa Sri Pushparama Purana Devapita Viharaya is a ancient Buddhist temple with an ancient Tampita Viharaya belonging to the Kandyan era. The temple lies between Dummalasuriya and Udubaddawa on the Madampe – Kuliyapitiya road.
Bibiladeniya Sri Maliyadeva Maha Pirivena is an ancient Buddhist temple now turned in to a Buddhist seat of learning with a ancient Tampita Viharaya belonging to the Kandyan era. The temple lies on the Marawila – Udubaddawa road, about 16 km from Marawila and 4 km from Udubaddawa.
Dethawa Sri Mahamuni Purana Viharaya is an ancient Buddhist temple with a Tampita Viharaya belonging to the Kandyan era. The temple lies about 14 km from Giriulla 5 km from Narammala.
According to legend, the anklets of goddess Pattini was also brought to Sri Lanka by the captured 12,000 Soli prisoners of king Gajabahu (112-134) which was beginning of the Pattini cult of Sri Lanka.
  Udubaddawa Shilapokkarani Purana Viharaya is an ancient Buddhist temple 16 km off Madampe  and 7 km off Kuliyapitiya with a Tampita Viharaya belonging to the Kandyan era.  To reach the temple from Madampe , travel 15 km on the
According to the the Central Environmental Authority this tree has lied on a bund of the irrigation reservoir built by king Vijayabahu III (1232-1236) of Dambadeniya kingdom. Thus this tree is about 800 years old.
Alawwa Paramaulla Purana Viharaya is an ancient Buddhist temple with a Tampita Viharaya 2.5 km off Alawwa with a Tampita Viharaya belonging to the Kandyan era. The Tampita Viharaya at Paramaulla Purana Viharaya is comparatively small and is built on six granite pillars. The Full width and the length of the Tampita Viharaya is taken up by the image house.
Passing the ruins of the palace of king Prakramabahu (1153-1186) and the other ruins of various temples of the ancient Panduwasnuwara kingdom, you will reach the Panduwasnuwara Rajamaha Viharaya.
Paluwella Angeerasuththararamaya Purana Viharaya is an ancient Temple with Tampita Viharaya from the Kandyan Era. Other granite ruins in the temple indicate an era even before the Kandyan kingdom.
Pahala Baladora Sri Nagarukkarama Purana Tampita Viharaya is an ancient Buddhist temple with a Tampita Viharaya belonging to the Kandyan era. This Tampita Viharaya has been restored in 2017.
  Nawinna Purana Tampita Viharaya is an ancient Buddhist temple with a Tampita Viharaya belonging to the Kandyan era. The temple lies about 4.5  km off Wariyapola and 24 km from Kuruanegala. To reach the temple from Kuruanegala, travel upto
Indulgoda Sri Pushparamaya Rajamaha Viharaya is an ancient Buddhist temple with a Tampita Viharaya belonging to the Kandyan era. This Tampita Viharaya was declared as a protected archaeological monument on the gazette dated 7th December 2001.
Uyanegama Sri Nagabodhi Rajamaha Viharaya is an ancient Buddhist temple with a Tampita Viharaya belonging to the Kandyan era. This Tampita Viharaya was declared as a protected archaeological monument on the gazette dated 24th July 2009.
  Medagama Kanda hill lies about 6 km south-east from Panduwasnuwara ancient Kingdom. At the top of this hill lies ruins of an ancient dagoba conserved by the department of Archeology in 1986. There is a strong belief that this
Kaluhendiwela Mayurawathi Tampita Rajamaha Viharaya is an ancient Buddhist temple with a Tampita Viharaya belonging to the Kandyan era. The small Tampita Viharaya built on 8 granite pillars was declared as a protected archaeological monument 7th December 2001.
Maspotha Purana Viharaya is an ancient Buddhist temple with a Tampita Viharaya belonging to the Kandyan era. This Tampita Viharaya was declared as a protected archaeological monument on the gazette dated 22nd November 2002.
Kudagalgamuwa Purana Viharaya is an ancient Buddhist temple with a Tampita Viharaya belonging to the Kandyan era. This Tampita Viharaya was declared as a protected archaeological monument on the gazette dated 25th April 1980.
Kongoda Bodhirajaramaya Purana Viharaya is an ancient Buddhist temple with a Tampita Viharaya belonging to the Kandyan era. The temple lies about 12 km from Kurunegala and 2 km off Barandana Junction on the Mallawapitiya – Keppetigolla road.
The Tampita Viharaya at the Kongahagedara Sri Bodhidrumaramaya Purana Viharaya is believed to be built during the latter part of the Kandyan kingdom. The Tampita Viharaya at Kongahagedara is built on 16 granite pillars.
Katupitiya Sri Nagarukkaramaya Purana Viharaya is an ancient Buddhist temple with a Tampita Viharaya belonging to the Kandyan era. The Tampita Viharaya at Katupitiya was declared as a protected archaeological monument by the gazette dated 22nd November 2002.
Kolamunna Sri Sugatharamaya Purana Viharaya is an ancient Buddhist temple with a Tampita Viharaya belonging to the Kandyan era.The Tampita Viharaya at Kolamunna is built on 8 granite stumps laid in 2 rows. There entrance to the image house is through a wooden flight of steps.
  Gammana Bodhirukkarama Purana Viharaya is an ancient Buddhist temple with a Tampita Viharaya belonging to the Kandyan era. The temple lies about 2 km off Pothuhera lying between Polgahawela and Kurunegala. From Pothuhera take the Kuriyampola road which lies
  Kalundawa in an ancient remote village which has come in to limelight during the recent past due the movie “Siri Parakum” which dramatize the life story king Parakramabahu II of Dambadeniya kingdom. According to legend prince Parakramabahu spent his
Kahatawilagedara Tampita Viharaya is an ancient Tampita Viharaya belonging to the Kandyan era which was declared as an Protected Archaeological Site by the government by the gazette dated 23rd February 1967.
  Sulugulu Rajamaha Viharaya at Kadawalagedara is an ancient temple with a  history going as far as the early Anuradhapura era. Based on a research carried out by the Rajarata University, this temple has been built during the reign of
The Tampita Viharaya at the Inguruwaththa Purana Viharaya is built on 2 feet 4 inches high 8 granite stumps during the era of king Kirthi Sri Rajasinghe (1747 – 1781). . A circumambulating path is built around the image house protected by a half height wall.
  Hiripathwella Mayurawathi Sri Bodhirajarama Purana Viharaya is an ancient Buddhist temple with a Tampita Viharaya belonging to the Kandyan era. The temple lies 6 km off Pothuhera and 11 km off Polgahawela between Wadakada and Pothuhera. To reach the
Hindhawa Sri Wijesundararamaya Purana Viharaya is an ancient viharaya with a Tampita Viharaya belonging to the Kandyan era. The temple lies 7 km off Wariyapola in the Bamunakotuwa area.
The Tampita Viharaya at the Hindagahawewa Wedaungala Purana Viharaya has been built during the Kandyan era. Some of the historical significance of this structure has been lost due to some restorations in the recent past.
  Ganangamuwa Sri Purvaramaya Purana Viharaya lies in the village of Ganangamuwa just 11 km away from Kuliyapitiya. The temple can be reached through Kuliyapitiya – Narammala road road by traveling upto Ganangamuwa (10km) and taking the Konduruwapola road.  Another
The Tampita Viharaya at the Edandawala Purana Viharaya has been built during the Kandyan era and consists of 2 floors. The Image house is built on tall 6-7 feet high granite pillars and a wall is built around the pillars creating a separate chamber below the image house.
Digampitiya Purana Tampita Viharaya is an ancient temple built during the Kandyan Era and lies about 7 km away from the Kurunegala town. The Tampita Viharaya at the Digampitiya Purana Viharaya was declared as an protected archaeological site in 2002.
The Tampita Viharaya at the Deekirikewa Purana Viharaya is built on 10 granite pillars. Cross beams have been laid across the pillars and 3 inch thick wooden planks have been laid across the beams to make the floor.
Galgamuwa Purana Viharaya is an ancient temple lying in the Alawwa Divisional Secretary’s Division in Galgamuwa, Maharachchimulla. The temple lie about 5 km off Matiyagane between Dambadeniya and Narammala.
Bulupitiya Sri Sugatharama Purana Viharaya lies in the village of Bulupitya in Uhumiya (Uhumeeya) on the Narammala – Kurunegala road. This temple has been built during the Kandyan Kingdom.
 
 

